    Part 1 - Create ML Model

    Plant Disease Detection: Part 1 Create a meachine model with TensorFlow¶

    In part 1, we will create a working machine learning with tensorflow by using real data used is scientific reasearch see here.

    What to exptect¶

    • Download dataset onto our machine
    • Inspect the downloaded dataset
    • Prepare the dataset to use in training our machine learning model
    • Create a machine learning model with TensorFlow
    • Quick evaluation of the trained model
    • Save and load the finished model
    • Make prediction with random data
    • (Optional) Convert the model into a TensorFlow lite model

    I have a question¶

    Any question related to the project please use the GitHub discussion page.

    Some common functions¶

    It might be very early to talking about any functions that will be used only later. You might skip this one first and circle back when a function is used.

    There are 2 types of function that we are using. The first one are utility functions such as for evaluating our trained model, or a function to predict random images. The other type of functions are callbacks used while training our machine learing model.

    plot_loss_curve()¶

    One method to evaluate model's performance is to look at its loss and accuarcy metrics. The plot_loss_curve() will plot 2 graphs for use. One for the the model's loss and one for the accuracy.

    Here are some examples how the loss curves look like.

    In [3]:
    Copied! 
    def plot_loss_curve(history):
  loss = history.history['loss']
  validation_loss = history.history['val_loss']

  accuracy = history.history['accuracy']
  validation_accuracy = history.history['val_accuracy']

  epochs = range(len(history.history['loss']))

  # Plot loss
  plt.plot(epochs, loss, label='training_loss')
  plt.plot(epochs, validation_loss, label='validation_loss')
  plt.title('Loss')
  plt.legend('Epochs')
  plt.legend()

  # Plot accuracy
  plt.figure()
  plt.plot(epochs, accuracy, label='training_accuracy')
  plt.plot(epochs, validation_accuracy, label='validation_accuracy')
  plt.title('Accuracy')
  plt.legend('Epochs')
  plt.legend()
    def plot_loss_curve(history): loss = history.history['loss'] validation_loss = history.history['val_loss'] accuracy = history.history['accuracy'] validation_accuracy = history.history['val_accuracy'] epochs = range(len(history.history['loss'])) # Plot loss plt.plot(epochs, loss, label='training_loss') plt.plot(epochs, validation_loss, label='validation_loss') plt.title('Loss') plt.legend('Epochs') plt.legend() # Plot accuracy plt.figure() plt.plot(epochs, accuracy, label='training_accuracy') plt.plot(epochs, validation_accuracy, label='validation_accuracy') plt.title('Accuracy') plt.legend('Epochs') plt.legend()

    predict_and_plot_random_image()¶

    The preduct_and_plot_random_image() function is use to test how well our model will perform will unseened image.

    Example of how the function looks like after executed.

    In [4]:
    Copied! 
    def predict_and_plot_random_image(model, file_name, image_shape=(224, 224)):
  # Load the image
  img = tf.io.read_file(file_name)
  # Decode image into a tensor with 3 color channels
  img = tf.image.decode_image(img, channels=3)
  # Resize the image
  img = tf.image.resize(img, size=[image_shape[0], image_shape[1]])
  # Rescale the image
  img = img/255.

  # Make prediction
  prob = model.predict(np.asarray([img]))[0]
  class_idx = np.argmax(prob)

  print(f"Prediction: the image is categorized to {class_names[class_idx]} with a {prob[class_idx]:.4f}% of confidence")
  plt.imshow(img)
  plt.figure()
  plt.show()
    def predict_and_plot_random_image(model, file_name, image_shape=(224, 224)): # Load the image img = tf.io.read_file(file_name) # Decode image into a tensor with 3 color channels img = tf.image.decode_image(img, channels=3) # Resize the image img = tf.image.resize(img, size=[image_shape[0], image_shape[1]]) # Rescale the image img = img/255. # Make prediction prob = model.predict(np.asarray([img]))[0] class_idx = np.argmax(prob) print(f"Prediction: the image is categorized to {class_names[class_idx]} with a {prob[class_idx]:.4f}% of confidence") plt.imshow(img) plt.figure() plt.show()

    Callbacks¶

    It might be very early to talking about any functions that will be used only later. You might skip this one first and circle back when a function is used.

    Callbacks functions is used during the training of a machine learning model. When testing multiple models it will be a good practice to define those as a function rather than repeatly code the same lines.

    We will use 3 callbacks in each trained model.

    1. Early Stopping: to stop train a model when certain critaria has reached

    2. Model Checkpoint: to save the current state during training

    3. Reduce Learning Rate: adjust the model's learning rate during training

    early_stopping()¶

    The EarlyStopping() used to stop training the model when the parameter assigned in monitor does't improve after a number of epochs as assigned in the patient parameter. The reason of choosing val_loss over accuracy is to prevent overfitting. It is more likely that over fitting occur when the accuracy going to a very high number while the loss is increasing. The trained model has fit all the trained data and hasn't generalized it.

    Parameters

    • monitor: model parameter to be monitored. In our case, we monitoring val_loss
    • patience: the amount of epochs (since the last epoch with the best result) to wait before to stop the training. We will stop after 3 epochs without any improvements.

    See also: tf.keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping

    In [5]:
    Copied! 
    def early_stopping(monitor='val_loss', patience: int = 3):
  early_stop =tf.keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(patience=patience, monitor=monitor)
  return early_stop
    def early_stopping(monitor='val_loss', patience: int = 3): early_stop =tf.keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(patience=patience, monitor=monitor) return early_stop

    model_checkpoint()¶

    Is to save the model checkpoint (as a checkpoint file not as a model) at an interval during the training. This checkpoints then can be used to continue to train the model later.

    Parameters

    • filepath: the target path to save each checkpoints
    • save_best_only: save the best model if the montior parameter is met. The model will be saved at the end of an epoch. Set it either to True or False.
    • save_weight_only: save the weight of the model. This happend during an epoch. set either True or False
    • monitor: model parameter to be monitored. In our case, we monitoring val_loss
    • verbose: to show a log message on the console when any checkpoint is saved. set 0 for not showing and 1 for showing a message

    See also: tf.keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint

    In [6]:
    Copied! 
    def model_checkpoint(path: str, monitor='val_accuracy'):
  checkpoint = tf.keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(path,
                                                  save_weights_only=False,
                                                  monitor=monitor,
                                                  save_best_only=True,
                                                  verbose=1)
  return checkpoint
    def model_checkpoint(path: str, monitor='val_accuracy'): checkpoint = tf.keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(path, save_weights_only=False, monitor=monitor, save_best_only=True, verbose=1) return checkpoint

    reduce_learning_rate()¶

    Parameters

    • monitor: model parameter to be monitored. In our case, we monitoring val_loss
    • patience: the amount of epochs (since the last epoch with the best result) to wait before adjust the learning rate. We will change the learning rate after 3 epochs if the model doesn't show any improvements.

    See also: tf.keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping

    In [7]:
    Copied! 
    def reduce_learning_rate(monitor="val_loss", min_learning_rate=0.001, verbose=1):
    reduce_lr = tf.keras.callbacks.ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor=monitor,
                                                     min_lr=min_learning_rate,
                                                     patience=3,
                                                     mode="min",
                                                     verbose=verbose)
    return reduce_lr
    def reduce_learning_rate(monitor="val_loss", min_learning_rate=0.001, verbose=1): reduce_lr = tf.keras.callbacks.ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor=monitor, min_lr=min_learning_rate, patience=3, mode="min", verbose=verbose) return reduce_lr

    Model 0: Base Model¶

    Create, Compile, and Run the Model¶

    In [18]:

    Evaluate Model¶

    The model has run over 20 epochs for more than an hour with the current gpu performance. The training loss went down under 0.02 with an accuracy of 0.99, where the validation loss is under 0.05 with an accuracy a bit over 0.98.

    First intuition might say that the model is overfitting. To prove the hypothesis we will use the model to predict some random images from the interent.

    def compare_model(model_history):
  # Plot training loss
  i = 0
  for m in model_history:
    epochs = range(len(m.history['loss']))
    loss = m.history['loss']
    plt.plot(epochs, loss, label=f'model_{i} training loss')
    i += 1
  plt.title('Training Loss')
  plt.legend('Epochs')
  plt.legend()

  # Plot Validation Loss
  i = 0
  plt.figure()
  for m in model_history:
    epochs = range(len(m.history['val_loss']))
    validation_loss = m.history['val_loss']
    plt.plot(epochs, validation_loss, label=f'model_{i} validation loss')
    i += 1
  plt.title('Validation Loss')
  plt.legend('Epochs')
  plt.legend()

  # Plot Training Accuracy
  i = 0
  plt.figure()
  for m in model_history:
    epochs = range(len(m.history['accuracy']))
    accuracy = m.history['accuracy']
    plt.plot(epochs, accuracy, label=f'model_{i} training accuracy')
    i += 1
  plt.title('Training Accuracy')
  plt.legend('Epochs')
  plt.legend()

  # Plot Validation Accuracy
  i = 0
  plt.figure()
  for m in model_history:
    epochs = range(len(m.history['val_accuracy']))
    validation_accuracy = m.history['val_accuracy']
    plt.plot(epochs, validation_accuracy, label=f'model_{i} validation accuracy')
    i += 1
  plt.title('Validation Accuracy')
  plt.legend('Epochs')
  plt.legend()
